metadata.name: Mono Vibration #25
metadata.description:
It's a unique and captivating generative artwork, created with the aid of AI, which adds a touch of innovation and dynamism to the piece. This black and white, high-contrast artwork showcases the interplay of sin waves, moirÃ© patterns, and Voronoi diagrams to create an engaging visual experience that stimulates the viewer's imagination.

The AI's creative input allows for the seamless integration of distinct visual elements and a dynamic composition that keeps the viewer's eyes moving across the canvas. Mono Vibration is a testament to the power of human-AI collaboration, blending the artist's vision with the AI's creative capabilities to produce a mesmerizing work of art that evokes a sense of depth, movement, and harmony.

metadata.name: the boxes we live in #395
metadata.description:
Throughout our lives we are placed in boxes that define who we are and limit how we think of ourselves. 

I am a father, husband, son, brother, friend. I am an artist, programmer, photographer, musician, designer, creator. I am a student and I am a teacher. I am a good person. I am a bad person. I am a human.

What boxes do you put yourself in, and do you let others put you in? Is it possible to break out of the boxes that define your life? Do you even want to? What's outside of these boundaries? What is at the center?

metadata.name: Leaf study #40
metadata.description:
This piece is an exploration of the mathematical rules that dictate plant growth as well as their photosynthesis. 

Features :

- Press 1 - 9 : change the pixel density ( to increase the size of the export ). the default value is 2. Beware hight resolution will slow down the piece

metadata.name: THE END #88
metadata.description:
An ode to our short lives & our even shorter years, a lingering feeling of it having escaped through our grasp as we were just about to comprehend its meanings, shoved into another cycle of life and death. Unlike our cosmos both above and below, the universe and the microscopic world - omnipresent and continuous; time almost feels like a prison on land, a boat without a sail in the sea, an astronaut without a spaceship - a binding of our mind and behaviour. As if we were too afraid to face the eternal chain of feedback loop that engulfs us all. So as this year comes to an end and another one begins, here is my last piece.

This year was full of surprises for all of us, packed with floods, fires, hurricanes, wars and amazing new discoveries! This piece was inspired by the constant yearning to escape into the endless space. And as James Web Telescope keeps discovering new stuff out there, it makes me question - is the big bang real? Or has it always been like this? Are we very close to discovering something new? What if just like time, space was just another loop? How do the different dimensions intertwine with each other? Despite all hardships, this year end seems to bring about hope - hope for a better exciting future. Hope that we might survive our doomsday. Hope that we might actually be ready to face the endless void beyond earthly time and space. 

And with that said I hereby introduce my last piece for 2022, the cosmic fidget spinner with melancholic 90s generative audio! 

Interactivity: 

Press M for the audio (Proceed with caution I am not really a musician)
Press P to check performance 
Press S to save a 1920x1920 screenshot 
Click and drag over the artwork to play around with the cosmic sculpture 

In case you are on the phone, you can use the invisible menu button at the top right corner of the frame for accessing all of the above functionality!    

And best of luck for 2023!

Jaalibandar '22

metadata.name: Digital Surrogates #84
metadata.description:
â€œAllan McCollumâ€™s Plaster Surrogates was a thought-provoking series of sculptures that examines the role of art in contemporary society. The sculptures are cast from plaster and painted to resemble frames, mats, and black rectangles, creating a visual illusion of empty picture frames. McCollum's intention with the surrogates was to comment on the mass production and consumption of art objects, as well as the way in which art is often valued for its social function rather than its inherent aesthetic qualities.â€

Continuing the integration of generative art and conceptual art, this work is a digital reproduction and inspiration of Plaster Surrogates - 1982 by noted conceptual artist, Allan McCollum.

Even though the original work had completely black rectangles, in this work, contrasting colors are used in some variations to increase the beauty. The dimensions and colors of the frames are calculated according to McCollum's original work. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

-----------

No images are used, created entirely by coding. Textures such as wood, canvas, and oil paint have been created to create a realistic look. Preview optimized for fxhash capturing system and full rendering can take up to several minutes, so I highly recommend checking out this artwork in high quality.


To save the artwork in high resolution, Open it in the live mode, it will be saved automatically after completion.

Made with p5js.
